Full Description:
In 1995  the end of the Cold War found the US Navy grappling with its role and its future. Dr. James Tritten ably articulated the value of naval doctrine in this historical survey for the Naval Doctrine Command. In subsequent decades  USN doctrine evolved in response to changing circumstances  in some instances successfully  in some instances not. The USN abandoned long-distance strike aircraft in a doctrinal pursuit of sorties-to-shore  wasted decades on a Littoral Combat Ship that was almost literally all doctrine  and saw its seakeeping readiness degrade at a level even more fundamental than the doctrinal. Today  the US Navy is faced with an existential threat from a peer competitor that can outrange it  outshoot it  and outbuild it. Getting naval doctrine right has never been more critical. Understanding its history is a necessary first step that will repay investment for anyone interested in American sea power: that is  American national power.

